choices.text:
running or bicycling—about 10 minutes each way. Our host suggested that we ask younger people in the town for example the police to show us the back roads [between the olive groves and corn fields] where bicyclists go. We chose to run, and our host led us. The halloumi cheese is so fresh and has a fuller flavor than in the states. It is the only cheese used in making luffa sponges. The bread toasts quickly once extracted from the ceramic oven. Combined with fresh jam and locally roasted coffee, we fill our stomachs with this delicious fare every morning!

Yes, the rice they gave us had a different fragrance; noticeably not mixed with herbs, but the rice you bought wasn’t fragrant either. Nuts? No, scratch! Not even small fruit; just 2 oranges, 3 apples, 3 bananas, and 6 tomatoes. Practical gardening: spreads close to each other

Flowers are essential to decorating the inner walls of the homes. A room without beauty? Not possible.

The only crops we saw were the citrus trees, two types of olives, tomatoes, corn, eggplant, and peppers. One incorporates bee colonies in his hives sited directly above the olive trees to capture their pollen–just ask him to show you by the road (see third-to-last picture)!

In Chamisean, we watched Tui’s family dry lemons on the ground beneath the tamarisks
